Part 1 - Understanding the mechanisms of ggplot In order to receive full credit, you must use ggplot syntax to answer the questions in Part 1.

Q1) The following code produces a scatterplot with pink points, even though we specified blue. Why arent the points blue? First, explain why this happens and then fix the code to correctly produce a scatterplot with blue points. ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) + geom_point(aes(colour = blue))

A1) The reason why the plot points are red instead of blue is the use of the aes function within the geom_point call. This is because of the difference between setting and mapping. The aes function takes in mappings from our data into our geom, when actually we want to set it in our geom instead, in order to get the points to be blue.

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) + geom_point(color = "blue")

df_mpg <- mpg
ggplot(mpg, aes(cty, hwy, color = year)) + geom_point() + labs(x = "City Mileage", y = "Highway Mileage", title= "Fuel Economy of Cars Manufactured in the Year 1999 and 2008")

ggplot(mpg, aes(average_mpg, class, color = year)) + geom_point() + labs(x = "Average MPG", y = "Class of Vehicle", title= "Average Fuel Economy of Cars Manufactured in the Year 1999 and 2008")

Q6) Are cars in 2008 more fuel efficient than cars in 1999? Use graphs and summary statistics to answer this question. Explain your graphs in context. A6) Using the average fuel economy, calculated by adding the city and highway mileage of a car and dividing the value by 2, youll see below that there are exactly 3 cars that have better average fuel efficiency than cars that were manufactured in 2008. These are compact and subcompact cars as well. However, the seem to be outliers compared to the rest of the dataset, so I cant conclusively say that cars manufactered in 1999 are more fuel efficient than cars. Along with that, after visualizing the data by class of vehicle, you can see that certain classes have gotten much more fuel efficient in 2008 compared to their 1999 counterparts, SUVs and midsized vehicles especially. After creating boxplots for Average MPG of cars manufactured in 1999 and 2008 on separate plots, you can see that the boxplots on the 2008 plot are indeed slightly higher than those in 1999, but the scales of the plots are definitely different, with the 2008 plot having a maximum value of 35 mpg, and the 1999 plot having a maximum value of 40 mpg. Again, the results seem inconclusive, most of the cars have a similar distribution of average mpg in both years, but since 1999 has the most fuel efficient cars among both (even if they are outliers), Id wager to say that cars manufactuered in 1999 are just as fuel efficient as cars manufactered in 2008, with some cars made in 1999 topping the charts for both years.

ggplot(mpg, aes(average_mpg, class, color = year)) + geom_point() + labs(x = "Average MPG", y = "Class of Vehicle", title= "Average Fuel Economy of Cars Manufactured in the Year 1999 and 2008")#Same graph used in question 5.

cars1999 <- subset(mpg, mpg$year == 1999)
cars2008 <- subset(mpg, mpg$year == 2008)

cars1999$averageMPG <- (cars1999$cty + cars1999$hwy)/2 
cars2008$averageMPG <- (cars2008$cty + cars2008$hwy)/2

ggplot(cars1999, aes(x =class, y = averageMPG)) + geom_boxplot() + labs(x = "Class of Vehicle", y = "Average MPG", title= "Average Fuel Economy of Cars Manufactured in the Year 1999 ")

Q7)Explore the diamonds dataset. What is the distribution of the variable price in this dataset? Are there any factors (or combination of factors) that seem to be highly correlated with price? Use graphs and summary statistics to answer this question.

A7) Initially I created a line graph of the price on the y axis vs.carat on the x axis, and just the result was just what I expected, with the price steadily increasing as the carat of the diamond increases. Next, I decided to see whether or not clarity was a major factor in the pricing of the diamonds. The scale on the legend reads from worst to best clarity quality, IF being the highest clarity. Up to a certain carat cut, IF diamonds are much more pricier than I1 diamonds, who are on the complete opposite end of the spectrum, however the carat of IF diamonds ends at around 2.2-2.25 carats, however I1 diamonds overtake all others in price once it passes the 4.5 carat mark. Surprisingly, the clarity and carat value of a diamond doesnt seem to correlate with the price as much as the cut, as you see on the fourth plot, where ideal cut diamonds top prices, up until the diamond sizes reach 2.6 carats. I conclude that the factor that correlates the most with price is the cut of the diamond, for most of the time, but other cuts do start to overtake it the higher the carat gets.
